subsection.p:
Split an argument into completely separate pieces. In the example below we have two cases. Either x \ge y or x \lt y:




      Show that if x and y are real numbers, then:




        max(x,y) = \dfrac{x+y + |x-y|}{2}



        min(x,y) = \dfrac{x+y - |x-y|}{2}








      We need to prove each claim separately for each case!

proof.p:
Suppose \sqrt{3} were rational. Then \sqrt{3} = \frac{a}{b} for some integers a and b \ne 0. Without loss of generality, assume \frac{a}{b} is reduced. Now

  3 = \frac{a^2}{b^2}


3b^2  = a^2

statement.p:
\to Assume that x = y, and consider:

   \dfrac{(x+y)^2}{4} \amp=  \dfrac{(x+x)^2}{4} 
   \amp=  \dfrac{(2x)^2}{4} 
   \amp=  x^2 
   \amp=  xy 

This shows that if x=y then xy=\dfrac{(x+y)^2}{4}.
